The call will be slightly different as this result below was a test and you can see data/2.5/weather in the URL which is on a current basis but ill be using data/2.5/forecast which will grab for the 5 upcoming days

This code chunk below was 5 hours in the making. The previous method I was trying was declaring table present like *"city <- c(), weather <-c() etc etc"* & then use nrows with the declared api-id/cities/url to create a path to the individual list attributes.
It was confusing as I was able to get info using:
*content <- content(response, as = "text") parsed_content <- fromJSON(content, flatten = TRUE* as IBM suggested, but when pulling the data the weather variables id/main/description/icon were not being extracted thus halting the whole process.
So I could see the file but couldn’t convert it. Turning to Google it seems someone ran into this issue & found the solution you see here. The help() for str_glue describes it as a powerful & elegant syntax for interpolating strings. I believe it. 

# these are the cities for which I want to hone in on
cities <- c("Brisbane", "Chicago", "Tokyo", "Seoul", "London", "Copenhagen", "Berlin")
# create an empty shell table that I'll put all the information into
main_df <- data.frame()
# Function to get weather forecast by city
get_weather_forecast_by_cities <- function(url) {
  web_content <- httr::GET(url)
  web_content <- content(web_content, "text")
  json_data <- fromJSON(web_content, flatten = TRUE)
  df <- as.data.frame(json_data)
  return(df)
}
# Iterate through each city to fetch and bind the data
for (city_name in cities) {
  url <- str_glue("http://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/forecast?q={city_name}&appid={api_id}&units=metric")
  main_df <- bind_rows(main_df, get_weather_forecast_by_cities(url))
}

Bike count stats by time

time_bike_counts <- dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT
                                     CASE
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 0 AND 2 THEN '00:00-02:59'
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 3 AND 5 THEN '03:00-05:59'
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 6 AND 8 THEN '06:00-08:59'
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 9 AND 11 THEN '09:00-11:59'
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 12 AND 14 THEN '12:00-14:59'
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 15 AND 17 THEN '15:00-17:59'
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 18 AND 20 THEN '18:00-20:59'
                                       WHEN CAST(HOUR AS INTEGER) BETWEEN 21 AND 23 THEN '21:00-23:59'
                                     END AS hour_block,
                                     ROUND(AVG(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT), 2) AS avg_bike_count,
                                     MEDIAN(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) AS median_bike_count,
                                     MAX(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) AS max_bike_count,
                                     MIN(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) AS min_bike_count
                                     FROM bike_seoul
                                     GROUP BY hour_block
                                     ORDER BY hour_block;")

Grouping Temp w/ Bike counts

temperature_grouping <- dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT
                                   CASE
                                   WHEN TEMPERATURE < -10 THEN '<-10'
                                   WHEN TEMPERATURE < 0 THEN '-10 to 0'
                                   WHEN TEMPERATURE < 5 THEN '0 to 5'
                                   WHEN TEMPERATURE < 15 THEN '5 to 15'
                                   WHEN TEMPERATURE < 30 THEN '15-30'
                                   ELSE '> 30'
                                   END AS temp_range,
                                   ROUND(AVG(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT), 2) AS avg_bike_count,
                                   MAX(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) AS max_bike_count,
                                   MIN(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) AS min_bike_count,
                                   SUM(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) AS sum_bike_count,
                                   COUNT(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) AS count_in_temp_bracket
                                   FROM bike_seoul
                                   GROUP BY temp_range
                                   ORDER BY TEMPERATURE;")

Rainfall & Snowfall Grouping

weather_grouping <- dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT
                               CASE
                               WHEN RAINFALL = 0 THEN 'No Rain'
                               WHEN RAINFALL < 5 THEN 'Light Rain'
                               WHEN RAINFALL < 15 THEN 'Moderate Rain'
                               ELSE 'Heavy Rain'
                               END AS rainfall_range,
                               CASE
                               WHEN SNOWFALL = 0 THEN 'No Snow'
                               WHEN SNOWFALL < 5 THEN 'Light Snow'
                               ELSE 'Moderate Snow'
                               END AS snowfall_range,
                               ROUND(AVG(VISIBILITY), 2) AS avg_visibility,
                               COUNT(VISIBILITY) AS occurances
                               FROM bike_seoul
                               GROUP BY rainfall_range, snowfall_range
                               ORDER BY RAINFALL, SNOWFALL;")

“Feels Like Analysis” for Seoul

feels_like_analysis <- dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT DATE,
    CASE
      WHEN FEELS_LIKE < 8 THEN 'Under 8'
      WHEN FEELS_LIKE < 12 THEN 'Under 12'
      ELSE '12 & above'
    END AS Feels_like_range,
    ROUND(AVG(TEMPERATURE), 2) AS avg_temp,
    MAIN, 
    DESCRIPTION AS forecast,
    COUNT(DESCRIPTION) AS occurrence

    forecast
  WHERE 
    CITY_NAME = 'Seoul'
  GROUP BY

SUMMARY

First off I really enjoyed putting into practice some of these SQL queries I’ve made. Majority of them were inspired by Alex the Analyst, especially the ones with CASE statement.
I created the first SQL query to put into practice the CASE statement about bike counts by time. But it started off only with just displaying the average count, then after seeing the results I immediately knew with an additional 3 lines of code I could get alot more insights about the data.
I also played around with putting basic aggregation functions within the queries just to see in practice. Using COUNT(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT) / 24 AS count, I could have easily done COUNT(DISTINCT DATE) but it’s not common in these courses that they explore this technique & I know Alex would be proud.
Seoul bike Data
It’s interesting to see that the highest bike usage is during the block of 6pm - 9pm, but between 3am-6aam is lowest to be expected. You can see a morning peak between 6am-9am most likely based of people getting to work.
Autumn is the only season where Holiday bike average/max is higher than non holiday.
DATE bike_usage_per_day avg_daily_temp
25/09/18 23350.00 17.49167
24/09/18 17259.00 17.82083
23/09/18 20060.00 19.41250
09/10/18 22130.74 15.00000
03/10/18 30349.00 17.24167

September 23 is Chuseok, which is Korean Thanksgiving. Which is one of the most significant holidays in Korea, the following day is the Seoul International Fireworks Festival, which attracts alot of tourism and locals. The final day must be an extended day which carries on the festive spirit. On the October 3rd is Hangul Day which commemorates the creation of the Korean alphabet and the 9th is Hangeul Day which both celebrate & honor the importance of the Korean alphabet.
Summer is the busiest season for bike count & Winter is the least.

    ROUND(AVG(B.TEMPERATURE), 2) AS avg_temp,
    ROUND(AVG(F.TEMPERATURE), 2) AS avg_temp_F,
    ROUND(AVG(B.HUMIDITY), 2) AS avg_humidity,
    ROUND(AVG(F.HUMIDITY), 2) AS avg_humidity_F,
    ROUND(AVG(B.VISIBILITY), 2) AS avg_visibility,

  LEFT JOIN forecast AS F 
    ON SUBSTR(B.DATE, 1, 5) = SUBSTR(F.DATE, 1, 5)

Regression analysis with XLminer

Temperatures relationship with ride count
Around 31.5% of variability of the ride count is explained by temperature(rSquared). With a multiple R being over 0 indicates a positive relationship, meaning the ride count increases with the temperature.
With the coefficients, the estimate ride count is 348 at 0 degrees, with a 29.95 increase for every degree goes up. Both the Significance F and p value, being less than 0.05 mean that its under 5 percent chance that these results are caused by random variance or noise. While it only accounts for 35% it shows temperature is an important factor in predicting bike rentals!

Rainfalls relationship with Ride Count
With only 1.6% of the variance in ride count explained by rainfall and a very close score to 0 at 0.12 meaning it has a very weak positive correlation. BUT for every mm increase of rain, ride count drops by roughly 72 and because the Significance F and p-value are below 0.05 probability of being random variance or noise means this does have a significant negative impact on ride count but relatively low contribution to the whole picture.

Wind Speeds relationship with Rainfall
Only 0.0387% of the variance in wind speed is explained by rainfall(rSquared), with a multiple R of 0.01 being super close to 0 it has a pointless positive correlation to rainfall. 0.06 significance F and p value means its not statistically significant. Even if the results aren’t what we are looking for it doesn’t mean its not worth looking into, this is with XLminer so results might be different in R.

Humidity’s relationship with Rainfall
With 5.59% of the variability in humidity explained by rainfall, it has multiplier R value of 0.23 giving it a relatively decent positive correlation. 57% is the level of humidity expected when there is no rainfall and humidity increases by 4.27% for every 1mm increase of rainfall. Despite being statistically significant, the impact of rainfall is low. Or is it? When you think about a 4.47% increase in humidity for every 1mm of rainfall increase, that is quite big impact. In my pivot table I recorded max rainfall for each season showing: 18mm in Autumn, 35mm in spring, 29.5mm in Summer and 9.5mm in Winter. BUT right next to it I recorded the average rainfall and no month has even 1mm average in rain. So the occurrence of rain doesn’t contribute to the overall variability that might cause humidity to fluctuate through out the year, but it does have an impact when it does rain. Full circle moment.

One-hot Encoding - a method to divide a categorical column into individual columns broken down by each of the distinct observations and turning them into a binary answer of 1 and 0 (yes and no), consider it like pivot long but without affecting the amount of rows. This helps deal with false ordinality, when it comes to seasons, holidays & hour’s, they shouldn’t be ranked.

cols <- c("SEASONS", "HOLIDAY", "HOUR")
# Function to create dummy variables
create_dummy_vars <- function(data, cols) {
  for (col in cols) {
    data <- data %>%
      mutate(dummy = 1) %>%
      spread(key = col, value = dummy, fill = 0)
  }
  return(data)
}
# Apply the function to the dataset
seoul_normalise <- create_dummy_vars(seoul_normalise, cols)

Use rsq() and rmse() functions to calculate R-squared and RMSE metrics for the two test results
When it comes to goals of a regression, there are other metrics to consider but two important ones are the RMSE & R-Squared.
Root Mean Standard Error is a measure of a model’s overall accuracy. It compares the model’s predicted values to the actual values, specifically looking at the residuals (the differences between predicted and actual values). RMSE is a good indication of how well the model captures the relationship between the dependent variable and the independent variables introduced in the model. Lower RMSE values indicate a better fit, seeing as the data is scaled from 0 - 1, I want to aim for under 10pct which would be 0.1

R-Squared is the measure that explains how much influence the independent variables have on the dependant variables, in this case, how much influence does weather have on rented bike counts. It ranges from 0 to 1, where 0 indicates that the model does not explain any of the variance in the dependent variable, and 1 indicates that the model explains all the variance. The capstone suggests 0.72 but I’ll aim higher

# Calculate R-squared for weather model
rsq_weather <- rsq(data = prediction_weather, truth = TRUTH, estimate = predictions_weather)

Polynomial Regression

When it comes to Polynomial regression, I interpret it with the example of travelling from point(a) to point(b). Where a SLR is a straight path that gets you to point(b) by going in one straight direction, like a highway. As you travel along the highway you might see in the distance objects in the landscape that you cant explain.
While polynomial is the thought you can get to the same point(b) but instead of going straight to point (b), you along the way pull into a different road(lets consider a scenic path by the river which in most cases loops back onto the main road) which allows you to get a better understanding of the landscape. While scenic path might explain the landscape to which you are travelling, the potential trade off of adding flexibility is complexity and a larger margin of potential misinterpretation(residual/noise).

Model Refinement
When I initially plotted the relationship between rented bike count and temperature, I couldn’t detect a curved polynomial (degree 2) trend. However, after standardizing the data, the variances are now better uniform, making the underlying relationships between variables more visible. The model below shows a standard lm_line in red, poly(x,2) in yellow, poly(x,4) in green & poly(x,6) in blue.

Fit a linear regression model lm_poly with higher order polynomial terms on the important variables (larger coefficients) found in the baseline model

This shows how polynomial & interaction terms work in regression, first if we look at the first line were it shows the interaction(this is at the first degree or the straight line relationship of both Temperature and dew point) between both independent variables, then on the following 3 lines its looking at temperatures higher degree against dew points first degree, then it restarts the poly term for temperature but looks at the second degree for dew point.
Going back to my half cooked analogy about taking the scenic drive by the river to get to point B & seeing the landscape which you couldn’t by taking the highway.
The different landscapes might have features that are related to one another like how the river supplies water for the animals in the area, you might see an animal drinking water from the river. That would be an interaction, you could see the animal not by the river 100% but now you know how it relates to to the river which gives you a better understanding of what you are seeing. Now looking at the top of the summary we have a residual range.
Residuals are the differences between the observed values and the predicted values from the model. They help us understand how well the model fits the data. Ideally, residuals should be randomly distributed with a mean of zero, indicating that the model’s predictions are accurate on average. Residual analysis can reveal patterns that suggest potential problems in the model, such as non-linearity, heteroscedasticity or outliers.

plot(lm_poly1$fit, which = 2, sub.caption = "")


The QQplot is a great way to visualise how your residuals are actually looking.
The hard black line is a make up of all the observation’s residual based on poly_model1 when looking at rainfall and visibility’s impact on ride count. It should be running along the dotted line, but around 2 on either side, the quantiles start to deviate from the line, from this it can be said that the model is missing alot of variables that could explain the ride count being either too low or too high.

plot(lm_poly1$fit, which = 3, sub.caption = "")


The scale location plot is a great way to check heteroscedasticity. In simpler terms, heteroscedasticity is an assumption that the model’s errors are consistently spread out across all predictions. Ideally, the errors (residuals) should be evenly scattered, indicating a constant variance.
In the Scale-Location plot, you’re looking at how well the model meets this requirement. The plot shows the fitted values on the X-axis and the spread of the residuals on the Y-axis.
If the red line in your plot dips at any point, it suggests that the residuals are not evenly spread out and that there are areas where the variance of errors is lower. So this model fails the heteroscedasticity assumption.

plot(lm_poly1$fit, which = 5, sub.caption = "")


This plot helps identify points that might have a big impact on the regression. Firstly most data points are clustered near the 0.0 mark on the x axis and within the -4 to 4 range on the y-axis.
Then we have the 4 dash line starting on the 0 intercept of the x and y axis which is cooks distance.
So the cooks distance is something that was briefly covered by Equitable Equations in his video on outliers as a means to identify high influence anomalies & determine if they should be removed.
In the video, he uses two side by side scatter plots with a regression line each with an outlier that to the naked eye could be perceived as a significant outlier. But he includes a second differently coloured regression line to show the difference when the outlier is removed from the dataset. One shows a great improvement to the regression line while the other doesn’t. He ends by stating this method being cooks distance is the way you can visualise it without that side by side comparison.
Not being a perfect model or anywhere close, but there is alot of outliers that the model is capturing.

Tuning of Lambda to find the best fit

Within the 3 regression models of Ridge, lasso and elastic net that I’m going to be exploring, the technique of tuning the lambda is different between the models by the method of how it deals with shrinking the regressions coefficients, helping reduce the models complexity & enhancing generalisation to the data.
Ridge: Applies a penalty to all coefficients evenly, ideal for addressing multi collinearity.
Lasso: Shrinks some coefficients to zero, effectively selecting key features and discarding irrelevant ones.
Elastic Net: Combines both penalties, offering a balanced approach that benefits from the strengths of both Ridge and Lasso.
Build different models using polynomial terms, interaction terms, and regularizations.

# This is the poly_model1 formula from above, lets see how it does with some tuning
lm_glmnet_formula1 <- formula(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT ~ . + 
                                poly(TEMPERATURE, 4) * poly(DEW_POINT_TEMPERATURE, 2) +
                                Autumn * `18:00` + 
                                Autumn * Holiday + 
                                poly(HUMIDITY, 4) * `19:00` + 
                                poly(SOLAR_RADIATION, 2) * `12:00`)
# Create cross-validation folds
set.seed(42)
folds <- vfold_cv(seoultrain, v = 10)

# Define the model with tuning parameters, have to create this but wont need to replicate every time
tune_time <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("glmnet")

# Define the workflow
wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_formula(lm_glmnet_formula1)

# Create the tuning grid, I only have to make this initially, once I make more models no need. The Lambda grid is stating the range of penalty I want to apply, so starting at 0% to 20%. The mixture is the different style of Lambda
lambda_grid <- seq(0, 0.2, length.out = 25)
mixture_grid <- seq(0, 1, length.out = 25)
tuning_grid <- expand.grid(penalty = lambda_grid, mixture = mixture_grid)

# Tune the model using the grid
suppressWarnings({grid_results1 <- tune_grid(
  wf %>% add_model(tune_time),
  resamples = folds,
  grid = tuning_grid,
  metrics = metric_set(rmse, rsq))
})

correlation_matrix <- cor(seoul_normalise, method = "pearson")

Pearson’s Correlation Coefficient
With this table I’m not going to display what it looks like, as it is just as large as that poly/interaction model summary above. The method is a formula to see relationship between variables between 1 and -1. 1 being 100% positive correlation(when one thing increase the other does) and -1 being a 100% negative correlation(when one goes down so does the other). So the sweet spot is more than 0.5 and less than -0.5 within the range. From there I found a couple of strong relationships being:
Humidity & visibility, temperature & Winter, Solar Radiation and 12:00 & Dew_Point_temperature with winter/Summer

lm_glmnet_formula4 <- formula(RENTED_BIKE_COUNT ~ . +
                                poly(TEMPERATURE,6) +
                                DEW_POINT_TEMPERATURE * Winter +
                                DEW_POINT_TEMPERATURE * Summer +
                                DEW_POINT_TEMPERATURE * TEMPERATURE +
                                TEMPERATURE * Winter + 
                                poly(SNOWFALL, 4) * TEMPERATURE +
                                poly(HUMIDITY, 4) * poly(DEW_POINT_TEMPERATURE, 2) +poly(TEMPERATURE,2) * HUMIDITY + poly(TEMPERATURE,2) * `03:00` + poly(SOLAR_RADIATION, 4) * `12:00`+
                                Summer * `18:00` + Autumn * Holiday +
                                poly(HUMIDITY, 4) * poly(VISIBILITY,2) +
                                Autumn * `18:00` + TEMPERATURE * `05:00` +
                                poly(RAINFALL, 4) * poly(WIND_SPEED, 2))
  wf4 <- workflow() %>% 
    add_formula(lm_glmnet_formula4)

Now I’ll create the solar radiation column and put in the avg from the SQL search based on the HOUR_INTERVAL column that I created, this one I have more control over and is abit more important when it comes to the data, as visualised time of data really impacts amount of solar radiation.

avg_solar <- function(hour_interval){
  case_when(
    hour_interval %in% c("00:00:00") ~0,
    hour_interval %in% c("03:00:00") ~0,
    hour_interval %in% c("06:00:00") ~0.09,
    hour_interval %in% c("09:00:00") ~1.2,
    hour_interval %in% c("12:00:00") ~1.82,
    hour_interval %in% c("15:00:00") ~1.01,
    hour_interval %in% c("18:00:00") ~0.06,
    hour_interval %in% c("21:00:00") ~0,
    TRUE ~ NA_real_
  )
}
seoul_forecast <- seoul_forecast %>% 
  mutate(SOLAR_RADIATION = avg_solar(HOUR_INTERVAL))

#Creating a new one-hot coding formula but this time for HOUR_INTERVAL
cols1 <- c("HOUR_INTERVAL")
dummy_time <- function(data, cols1) {
  for (col in cols1) {
    data <- data %>% 
      mutate(dummy = 1) %>% 
      spread(key = col, value = dummy, fill = 0)
  }
  return(data)
  }
seoul_forecast <- dummy_time(seoul_forecast, cols1)
#I'm putting the values from the corresponding hour interval into new columns.

Project Close-Out Summary

Throughout this project, I utilized various forms and models of regression to achieve an rSquared value of 77.8% correlation and an RMSE of 8.27% between rented bike counts and weather.
I was suppose to additionally develop a dashboard using the leaflet package, but there was no training of leaflet in the course. IBM provided the code to build the UI/server + leaflet code but I was uncomfortable presenting it as my own work. Alternatively, I focused on using model results to forecast ride counts and validated them against actual ride counts, achieving close and accurate predictions. This is something not included in the original capstone but I had to make up for the dashboard.
I applied newly learned methods in data preparation, web scraping, visualization, creating functions and SQL.
From the results I found Summer to being the most active season for bike sharing, winter being the lowest & Autumn having the most variance/fluctuation in patterns which led its coefficient absolute value as the highest amongst the seasons.
While it could be easy to assume Temperature has the most impact: but rainfall, humidity & dew point temperature influence is higher when it changes against the average or expected.
Holiday’s appear to have a negative impact on bike usage with the exception of Autumn. Seoul celebrates 18 days of holidays
